tball leagues and by players. Juxtaposing material from interviews with football players and administrators and from media files and legal cases, he explores the discrepancies between the players’ own experiences and the institutional handling of disciplinary matters in junior, university, and professional football leagues across the country.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCanadian footballxLaw and legislation. 0aFootball playersxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada. 0aSoccer playersxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada. 0aSportsxLaw and legislationzCanada. 7aLAW / Sports.2bisacsh  aCFL.  adrugs.  asport.  aviolence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781927356548423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781927356548/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles